{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Reviewer dispatch sends the same source document and correct reviewer-specific instruction pack to each reviewer role.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: \"dispatch sends the same source document and correct reviewer-specific instruction pack to each reviewer role.\" Slot B: handoff boundary (orchestrator -> per-reviewer request builder). Slot C: if lowered to Unit, a real failure can be missed where wiring swaps instruction packs between roles even though each builder function passes in isolation. Rejection gate: rejected System because behavior text does not require real network/subprocess/OS effects; rejected Agentic because correctness here is payload routing, not model-output quality. Final label: Integration due Slot B handoff and Slot C cross-module misrouting miss.","test_description":"Run dispatcher with in-process fakes for the three reviewer clients; assert each outbound invocation received identical document bytes/content hash and the role-correct instruction pack, and that role-to-pack mapping is not swapped under parallel dispatch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The live clause extractor identifies key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Slot A: \"live clause extractor identifies key terms...\" Slot B: model-output boundary (real LLM extraction quality). Slot C: if lowered to Integration, a stubbed extractor can always return expected entities and hide failures on ambiguous phrasing/formatting in real contracts. Rejection gate: rejected Workflow because behavior covers one reviewer decision, not multiple agentic stages chained. Final label: Agentic due Slot B model-output dependence and Slot C stub-masks-quality miss.","test_description":"Call the real clause extractor model on a labeled contract set with varied legal phrasing; assert required entities are extracted with attribution and acceptable recall thresholds for parties/dates/obligations/penalties.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Risk-policy configuration is passed correctly to the risk assessor invocation.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: \"Risk-policy configuration is passed correctly to the risk assessor invocation.\" Slot B: handoff boundary (policy config serialization and invocation wiring). Slot C: if lowered to Unit, you can miss failures where config keys are renamed/dropped during module integration although local config builder tests pass. Rejection gate: rejected System because no requirement for real HTTP/subprocess behavior; rejected Agentic because this behavior validates invocation payload, not policy judgment quality. Final label: Integration due Slot B handoff and Slot C serialization/wiring miss.","test_description":"Wire orchestrator + risk-invocation module with a fake assessor endpoint/client; send non-default policy config and assert exact transmitted policy fields/values (including nested thresholds and toggles) match expected invocation schema.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The live risk assessor flags language that is problematic under policy, including indirect or euphemistic phrasing.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Slot A: \"live risk assessor flags language... including indirect or euphemistic phrasing.\" Slot B: model-output boundary (semantic interpretation quality). Slot C: if lowered to Integration, deterministic fixtures will not reveal misses on paraphrased/euphemistic risk language that only real model behavior exposes. Rejection gate: rejected Workflow because this is a single reviewer’s judgment, not a multi-step agent pipeline. Final label: Agentic due Slot B model-output dependence and Slot C semantic-generalization miss.","test_description":"Run real risk assessor against a curated set containing explicit and euphemistic risky clauses mapped to policy expectations; evaluate true-positive/false-negative behavior and verify flagged spans correspond to problematic language.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Jurisdiction and regulatory profile are passed correctly to the compliance checker invocation.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: \"Jurisdiction and regulatory profile are passed correctly to the compliance checker invocation.\" Slot B: handoff boundary (context propagation into compliance request). Slot C: if lowered to Unit, a real failure can be missed where jurisdiction/profile are defaulted or overwritten when modules compose request context. Rejection gate: rejected System because behavior text is about parameter passing, not real network/OS effects; rejected Agentic because it does not evaluate model compliance reasoning quality. Final label: Integration due Slot B handoff and Slot C context-propagation miss.","test_description":"Execute compliance invocation path with mixed jurisdiction/profile inputs using an in-process fake compliance client; assert transmitted request contains exact jurisdiction code, regulatory profile identifiers, and no fallback/default substitution.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.14,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The live compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all configured regulatory requirements.",